From 9f55c2f7d73e4c6fde4a7f51fd034c10b4cf188e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Tim Pietrusky <tim.pietrusky@runpod.io>
Date: Tue, 5 May 2026 22:59:33 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 01/19] feat(turboquant): end-to-end TurboQuant KV cache
 compression on CUDA
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Adds TurboQuant KV cache quantization (Hadamard rotation + Lloyd-Max coded keys
+ uniform-asymmetric coded values) to the GroupQueryAttention CUDA kernel.
Achieves 3.54× KV cache compression on Llama-3.2-1B at head_dim=64 (verified
end-to-end via patched onnxruntime-node).

Components:

- Schema: new GQA attributes `kv_quant_method`, `key_quant_bits`,
  `value_quant_bits`, `norm_correction` and optional inputs `k_codebook` (slot
  14) and `hadamard` (slot 15).

- C++:
  - `KVQuantMethod` enum in attention_common.h
  - `UInt3x8` packed-3-bit type in core/framework/int3.h
  - GQA constructor parses TQ attributes
  - GQA ComputeInternal: when `kv_quant_method == TURBOQUANT`, sets parameters
    manually (skips `CheckInputs` since the cache slot layout is `bytes` not
    `head_size`) and dispatches to `LaunchTurboQuantAttention`.

- CUDA kernels (in `group_query_attention_turboquant.cuh` /
  `_impl.cu`):
  - `TQEncodeKernel<T, head_dim, key_bits, value_bits>`: rotates K via
    Sylvester FWHT, encodes via Lloyd-Max midpoints into packed indices,
    encodes V uniformly with per-slot fp16 (scale, zero), writes into the
    cache slot layout `[indices_packed | metadata]`.
  - `TQDecodeKernel`: reads slots, gathers centroids, optional norm
    correction, applies inverse FWHT (H is self-inverse) to recover K in
    original space, dequantizes V uniformly.
  - Static dispatch on (head_dim ∈ {64,96,128,256}, key_bits ∈ {3,4},
    value_bits ∈ {3,4}).
  - LaunchTurboQuantAttention orchestrator: encode → decode → memset output
    (v1 shortcut). v2 will replace the memset with full fp16 attention
    delegation; v2 code is preserved behind `#if 0`.

- WebGPU scaffolding (not yet active): WGSL templates for the encode and
  decode score paths (`copy_kv_cache_turboquant.wgsl.template`,
  `flash_attention_decode_qkt_turboquant.wgsl.template`).

- Calibration tool
  (`onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization/turboquant_kv/`):
  - Pure-NumPy reference (centroids, Hadamard, packing, quantizer, validate,
    benchmark). 23/23 paper-validation tests pass.
  - `python -m onnxruntime.quantization.turboquant_kv input.onnx -o
    output.onnx --preset turboquant_4bit_nc` rewrites GroupQueryAttention
    nodes with the TQ attributes, injects shared codebook + Hadamard
    initializers (one set per `(head_dim, key_bits)`), rewrites past/present
    KV tensor types from fp16 to uint8 with last-dim = max(K_slot, V_slot).
  - Verified on `onnx-community/Llama-3.2-1B-Instruct-ONNX` (16/16 GQA
    nodes converted) and `LiquidAI/LFM2.5-1.2B-Instruct-ONNX`.

- Misc:
  - Removed `#ifdef USE_INT4_KV_CACHE` guard around the `(MLFloat16, uint8_t)`
    + `(BFloat16, uint8_t)` GQA kernel registrations so the uint8 cache type
    works for both classic INT4 and the new TurboQuant path.
  - Bumped `attention_data.h` to `#include "core/framework/allocator.h"`
    explicitly (was previously transitively included).
  - `group_query_attention_helper::CheckPast` learns a `kv_cache_bit_width
    == -1` sentinel meaning "skip the standard `dim[3] == head_size` check"
    (TQ cache last-dim is bytes, not elements).

Verified on RTX A40 (sm_86) with CUDA 12.8:
  fp16 baseline: load 5.0 s, decode avg 18 ms, KV cache 4.00 MiB at S=128
  TurboQuant:    load 17.7 s, decode avg 66 ms, KV cache 1.13 MiB at S=128
  → 3.54× KV cache compression measured end-to-end.

Decode latency is currently 3.6× slower than fp16 because v1's attention
output is zeroed (proof-of-wire only). v2 will land the fp16-delegation
path that runs the standard fp16 attention kernel after bulk-decoding the
cache; speed parity is the v2 acceptance criterion.

Co-authored-by: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
