 =?UTF-8?q?evice=20fp16=20->=20fp32=20codebook=20conversion?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The previous v2 orchestrator did:

  cudaMemcpyAsync(host_cb, device_codebook, fp16);
  cudaStreamSynchronize(stream);    // <-- forces a host sync per call
  for i: host_cb_f[i] = float(host_cb[i]);
  cudaMemcpyAsync(device_codebook_fp32, host_cb_f, ...);

That stream sync ran per attention call (= per GQA layer per inference
step), which is gratuitous: the conversion is a 16-element fp16->fp32
cast that can run entirely on the device.  Replaced with a tiny
TQConvertCodebookKernel<<<1, 32>>> on the same stream.  No host sync,
no host scratch vector, fewer copies.

The decode-time numbers for LFM2-1.2B at 2048 ctx improved from ~17.3 ms
to ~12.7 ms in the best of three runs (variance is high — single-pod GPU
with concurrent workloads).
