From 9449f90205be55ad5e40e9f17ec30971b52f02f4 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Tim Pietrusky <tim.pietrusky@runpod.io>
Date: Wed, 6 May 2026 09:54:40 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 06/19] turboquant(cuda): apply inline RoPE for do_rotary=1 GQA
 models
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The standard QkvToContext path applies rotary embeddings to Q and K via
LaunchUnpackRoPEAppend before writing the cache. The TQ orchestrator
bypasses that helper, so when the GQA op carries do_rotary=1 (LFM2,
LFM2.5, Qwen3 ONNX exports) the cache stored positionless K and Q never
saw the rotation, producing near-random logits even when no NaN
appeared.

Fix: when do_rotary=1, allocate scratch Q and K buffers, apply
LaunchRotaryEmbeddingKernel with position_ids_format=2 (positions
derived from past_sequence_lengths[b] + s), and feed the rotated
buffers through the encode/attention path. Past slots in present_kv
are still byte-copied from past_kv as before — they were RoPE-rotated
at their original write step, so the FWHT-quantized representation
still reconstructs the right rotated K.

Constraints:
- Currently fp16-only. The shared rotary helper is instantiated for
  `half`, `BFloat16`, and `float`, but TQ is templated on T = `half` or
  `__nv_bfloat16`. The CUDA bf16 type doesn't match ORT's BFloat16
  wrapper at the linker level, so we gate the rotary call behind
  `if constexpr (std::is_same<T, half>::value)`. Adding bf16 support
  is a one-line rotary_embedding_impl.cu instantiation when needed.
- Quality on LFM2-1.2B improves from cos sim 0.45 → 0.47 (still poor;
  the dominant remaining error comes from 4-bit V quantization on
  unscaled v_proj outputs that overflow fp16 reconstruction). Llama
  numbers (0.99526) are unaffected — those models don't carry
  do_rotary=1 so the new path is dormant.
