From 509f3469b8101728be1a047c557a8d82f471dbcc Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Tim Pietrusky <tim.pietrusky@runpod.io>
Date: Wed, 6 May 2026 10:24:25 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 07/19] =?UTF-8?q?turboquant(cuda):=20v4-lite=20=E2=80=94?=
 =?UTF-8?q?=20fused=20FlashAttention-style=20kernel=20with=20online=20soft?=
 =?UTF-8?q?max?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Replaces the v3.5 split (TQScoresKernel + TQSoftmaxRowKernel +
TQOutputKernel) with a single TQFlashAttentionKernel that walks K_full
and V_full in tiles of kBlockK rows and keeps a running (max, sum, acc)
trio per (b, h, s_q) output block. The SxS scores buffer is never
materialised — at S=4096 that buffer was ~2 GB per attention call and
~6 GB of incidental HBM read/write traffic per layer, which the profile
identified as the dominant cost of the prompt step.

Algorithm: standard FlashAttention-2 pattern. Per output block:
  m = -inf, l = 0, acc = 0
  for tile in K/V step kBlockK:
    score[s] = (Q . K[s]) * scale (causal-masked)
    m_new = max(m, max_s score)
    alpha = exp(m - m_new)
    l = l*alpha + sum_s exp(score-m_new)
    acc = alpha*acc + sum_s p_s * V[s]
    m = m_new
  out = acc / l

Static dispatch on (head_size, kBlockK):
  head_size 64  -> kHeadDim 64,  kBlockK 64
  head_size 128 -> kHeadDim 128, kBlockK 64
  other         -> v3.5 split kernels (unchanged)

The scores buffer is also no longer allocated when the fused path is
taken (head 64 / 128). Save 2 GB of cudaMallocAsync per attention
call at S=4K.

Numbers (LFM2-1.2B prompt step on RTX A40, median of 3):

  context | fp16 ms | TQ v3.5 ms | TQ v4-lite ms | gain |
  --------|---------|------------|---------------|------|
       24 |    13.5 |       18.4 |          19.3 | -5%  |
      256 |    23.3 |       36.4 |          35.7 |  2%  |
     1024 |    76.5 |      157.1 |         157.1 |  0%  |
     4096 |   248.4 |     1748.0 |        1564.5 | 12%  |

The gain at 4K is real but smaller than expected (~12% prompt-step
speedup). Reason: each (b, h, s_q) block still reads K_full and V_full
for the full sequence, so total K/V HBM traffic is unchanged at
O(S^2 * D) — the win is just from not materialising scores. Real
FlashAttention-2 tiles s_q as well, sharing K/V loads across multiple
queries via shared-memory reuse and tensor cores. That's the next
optimisation step (v5) and would require the per-head-dim thread-block
to also keep a strip of consecutive Q rows, plus wmma intrinsics.

Decode-step is essentially unchanged (within noise). The thread-0
serial reduction inside each tile is the main overhead; replacing it
with a warp shuffle would recover ~10% on short sequences.

Quality on LFM2 (cos sim vs fp16 on a 24-token real prompt) shifted
from 0.471 to 0.483 — within the run-to-run variance, no regression.
Llama numbers (0.99526) unaffected because that path uses head_size=64
too and still goes through the same fused kernel.
