MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

ROOT CAUSE OF THE LFM2 QUALITY ISSUE.

The TQEncodeKernel was reading K_in / V_in with BNSH stride:

  in_off = ((b * n_kv_heads + h) * new_seq_len + s_new) * head_dim

But ORT's GroupQueryAttention op delivers K and V in BSNH layout — the
projection outputs are flat (B, S, N_kv * H_kv) and stride accordingly:

  in_off_correct = ((b * new_seq_len + s_new) * n_kv_heads + h) * head_dim

With the wrong stride, every (b, h, s) block read a slice that
interleaved values from different head/sequence positions. The encoded
slot was effectively garbage, the FWHT roundtrip produced near-random
K vectors, and per-layer attention output landed at cos sim 0.18 vs
fp16. After the fix, every layer hits cos sim > 0.97 and the final
logits agree at 0.996 cos sim with argmax matching fp16.

Why Llama-3.2-1B previously reported 0.99 cos sim despite this bug:
the Llama numbers came from a synthetic-Gaussian unit test that
generated K/V already in BNSH layout (matching the wrong stride by
coincidence). It never exercised real model inference where ORT
hands the kernel BSNH-layout K/V. LFM2 inference exposed the bug
immediately because it actually runs through the GQA op end-to-end.

Validation, real prompt "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.":

  fp16 baseline argmax: 2479 (' There')
  TQ-v2     argmax:    2479 (' There')   ✓ match
  full-vocab cos sim:  0.99611
  top-10 agreement:    8/10

Per-layer (all 6 GQA layers in LFM2-1.2B):

  layer    cos sim
  L2       0.99063
  L5       0.98637
  L8       0.98673
  L10      0.98807
  L12      0.98467
  L14      0.97592

Multi-step decode (8 generation steps after a 64-token prompt) now
produces varied, sane tokens with no NaN: [1191, 7, 62343, 2454, 5135,
7905, 7905, 24222]. Previously every step after step 1 produced 0
because the attention output was so corrupted it tipped into NaN via
the saturation clamps.

This change also drops three temp env-var debug overrides
(WANDLER_TQ_DISABLE_ROTARY, WANDLER_TQ_FORCE_V35) introduced earlier
in this session for bisection.
