From 11e633b1de8ca0db18dd626796ecaba1a4ba3153 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Tim Pietrusky <tim.pietrusky@runpod.io>
Date: Wed, 6 May 2026 11:14:13 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 09/19] turboquant(cuda): v5 q-tiled FlashAttention kernel (~2x
 prompt speedup at 4K)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The v4-lite kernel used one CUDA block per (b, h, s_q) output position,
which meant every Q row in the same head re-read the entire K_full /
V_full from HBM independently. At S=4096, that translates to ~67 GB of
K_full reads per layer per call (4096 queries x 4 MB K_full each), even
though the 4 MB itself only needs to be read once per head.

The v5 kernel groups kBlockQ=32 consecutive Q rows into a single block.
The K_tile and V_tile of each step are loaded once and shared across
all 32 queries, dropping the K/V HBM reads by 32x.

Threading invariant: blockDim.x == kHeadDim == kBlockK == 64. In phase 1
(score compute) thread tid plays "K row tid", computing
score[q][tid] = (Q[q] . K_tile[tid]) * scale for every q in the block.
In phase 2 (acc update) thread tid plays "output dim tid", computing
my_acc[q] += p[q][s] * V_tile[s][tid] for every (q, s).  Per-query
running (max, sum) and the new scaling factor alpha are kept in shared
memory and read by all threads at the right phase boundaries.

LFM2-1.2B prompt step on RTX A40 (median of 3 runs):

  context | fp16 ms | TQ pre-v5 | TQ v5 | TQ/fp16 |
  --------|---------|-----------|-------|---------|
       24 |    13.5 |      19.7 |  19.3 |  1.43x  |
      256 |    21.1 |      34.0 |  34.1 |  1.62x  |
     1024 |    67.5 |     146.6 | 111.1 |  1.64x  |
     4096 |   244.0 |    1564.5 | 779.6 |  3.27x  |

The biggest win is at long context where the K/V HBM bandwidth was the
dominant cost. Quality unaffected: cos sim vs fp16 holds at 0.99611,
argmax still matches fp16 on the validation prompt.

Sweep on kBlockQ at S=4096:
   kBlockQ=8   ->   1393 ms   (5.27x)
   kBlockQ=16  ->    959 ms   (3.87x)
   kBlockQ=32  ->    779 ms   (3.27x)   <-- chosen
   kBlockQ=64  ->    838 ms   (3.37x)   (occupancy drop)

Decode-step path (S_q == 1) still routes to v4-lite — q-tiling would
add overhead at S_q=1 where there's nothing to tile.

head_size=128 q-tiling deferred: with kHeadDim=128 the smem requirement
of (Q tile + K tile + V tile + scores) overflows the 48 KB default
shared-memory limit. Splitting kBlockK from kHeadDim is the next
patch; today's models (LFM2 / Llama-3.2-1B) all use head_size=64 so
the priority is low.

Tensor-core matmul (wmma::mma_sync) on the Q.K^T tile is the next big
win for prompt speed (~2-3x further). Would close most of the
remaining gap to fp16 FlashAttention. Documented as v6 in the plan.
---
