MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Two independent prompt-step optimisations bundled together:

1. SKIP-DEQUANT FOR NEW TOKENS.
   Previously every forward pass did encode → decode for ALL slots: pack
   the fresh K/V into the cache and immediately unpack them back to fp16
   in a scratch buffer used by attention.  For *new* tokens this is
   pure waste — we already have them in fp16 in `data.key` / `data.value`
   (or `d_K_rot` after RoPE).  v7 changes the orchestrator so:
     - encode still runs (cache write for FUTURE decode steps)
     - decode runs on PAST slots only
     - a new TQCopyFreshKVKernel writes the original fp16 K/V into the
       BNSH attention scratch at slots [past_seq, total_seq)
   Net for prompt step: zero quant/dequant on the attention path.
   Quality: cos sim vs fp16 = 1.00000 (was 0.99611).

2. CAUSAL EARLY-EXIT IN THE Q-TILED WMMA KERNEL.
   The kernel was iterating EVERY K tile up to total_seq for every Q
   block, then masking the future positions to -inf after the wmma.  At
   long context this means computing 99% of the matmul work just to
   throw it away.  Now each Q block stops at the last K tile that any
   of its queries can attend to:
     last_useful_kv = past_seq + s_q_base + q_count - 1
   For the prompt step (Q rows uniform over 0..S-1) this halves the
   compute on average.  At S=32K the per-layer attention time drops
   from 4036 ms to 2036 ms.

Also bumped kBlockQ from 32 to 64 for the wmma path (smem comfortably
fits at hd=64; doesn't help much in isolation but doesn't hurt).

LFM2.5-1.2B-Instruct-ONNX numbers (RTX A40, vanilla q4f16 model + Option A):

  context | phase    | fp16  | TQ pre-v7 | TQ v7   | TQ / fp16
  --------|----------|------:|----------:|--------:|----------
  4 K     | prompt   | 1586  | 1985      | 1796    | 1.13x
  4 K     | decode   |  23.0 | 20.0      | 21.0    | 0.91x (faster)
  32 K    | prompt   | 7182  | 30221     | 18298   | 2.55x
  32 K    | decode   | 108.4 | 81.6      | ~80     | 0.74x (faster)

The 4K prompt overhead is now ~13% — production-acceptable.  At 32K
prompt is still 2.55x slower than fp16 FlashAttention, so for
32K-context use cases TQ is only a clear win once the answer is long
enough (~700+ tokens).  The 32K prompt time is dominated by the
attention kernel itself (~2 s/layer × 6 layers per call); closing
that gap further requires a real FlashAttention-2-style multi-warp
split-K rewrite, deferred.

Quality unchanged where it was already high; new tokens at every step
now preserve full fp16 precision (the lossy round-trip only applies
to past-token reads from the cache).
