Subject: [PATCH 16/19] turboquant(cuda): vectorize K/V smem loads in v4-lite +
 v6 wmma decode kernels
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Each thread now loads ONE full K/V row via uint4 (16-byte = 8-fp16
per transaction) instead of the older "thread tid loads column tid
for every row" scalar pattern. At kHeadDim=64 this is 8 vector loads
per thread instead of 64 scalar loads, with the full row staying as
a single coalesced HBM burst.

Decode-kernel speedup on LFM2.5-1.2B-Instruct-ONNX, RTX A40 (median of 3 runs):

  context | fp16 decode | TQ pre  | TQ vectorised | TQ vs fp16
  --------|------------:|--------:|--------------:|-----------
  32 K    |    128 ms   |  125 ms |     74 ms     |  1.73x faster
  64 K    |    230 ms   |  188 ms |    137 ms     |  1.68x faster

Quality unchanged: cos sim vs fp16 still 1.00000.

Same vectorisation pattern applied to v6 wmma (used for continuation
prefill). v6 path didn't have a measurable change in our benches —
its prompt-step variant only fires when past_seq > 0 and S_q > 1
which our standard bench doesn't exercise.

Cheap, low-risk optimisation (no algorithmic change). Next candidates
in priority order: cp.async double-buffered loads, kBlockK=128 tiles,
constant-memory codebook for encode/decode helper kernels.
