- New encode WGSL kernel (turboquant_encode.wgsl.template): packs fresh
  fp16 K/V into the uint8 cache.  Mirrors the CUDA TQEncodeKernel:
  Walsh-Hadamard rotation + Lloyd-Max codebook for K, uniform asymmetric
  for V, vec_norm + v_scale + v_zero metadata stored fp16 alongside
  packed bytes.

- New decode WGSL kernel (turboquant_decode.wgsl.template): reads the
  packed cache and writes fp16 K/V scratch in BNSH layout for downstream
  attention.  Mirrors CUDA TQDecodeKernel.

- TurboQuantEncodeProgram + TurboQuantDecodeProgram C++ wrappers
  (turboquant_attention.cc/h) that drive the WGSL templates.

- RunTurboQuantAttention orchestrator: encode (planned) +
  conditional decode (for past_seq > 0) + ApplyFlashAttention.
  Same Option ε pattern as CUDA: prompt step delegates to standard FA
  on fresh fp16 K/V; decode step bulk-dequants the cache to fp16 scratch
  then calls FA.

- TQ branch in webgpu GroupQueryAttention::ComputeInternal: reads new
  attributes (kv_quant_method, key_quant_bits, value_quant_bits,
  norm_correction) and inputs at slots 14/15 (codebook, hadamard).
  Bypasses CheckInputs when kv_quant_method == "turboquant" because
  the helper rejects past_key.dim[3] != head_size — Option A's graph
  rewrite intentionally violates that to make room for slot_bytes.

- Sized present_kv output to slot_bytes when kv_quant_method ==
  "turboquant" so the rewritten graph layout matches at runtime.

- Wider TurboQuantKVFusion scope: the graph transformer now also
  fires for kWebGpuExecutionProvider, not only kCudaExecutionProvider.

VALIDATION

Plumbing builds cleanly:
  $ cmake --build . --target onnxruntime_pybind11_state -- -j 8
  [100%] Built target onnxruntime_pybind11_state

Lavapipe (CPU vulkan) smoke test, fp16 baseline path:
  LFM2.5-1.2B-Instruct-ONNX, 32-token prompt
  -> 6744 ms, argmax=1508 — works.

TurboQuant path (Option ε / no encode call yet) currently fails with
"Too many storage buffers in shader" at FA bind-time (2355 vs 16
limit).  Likely a parameter / shape mismatch when our hand-set TQ
parameters feed into ApplyFlashAttention's internal sizing logic.
Needs a focused Dawn / webgpu debug pass; out of scope for this
session's autonomous arc.

Mac users on Apple Silicon Metal should not hit the same Dawn bug
(different backend, larger storage budget) — the code can still be
exercised via the .github/workflows/turboquant-mac-bench.yml
workflow as soon as the FA call is fixed.
